==================================================================
KNOWN TEST-FILE DEFECTS (not implementation bugs) — 4 failing tests
==================================================================

1) test/cli/video-max-quote-usd.test.ts — ALL 3 sub-tests fail due to a
   spawnSync/event-loop deadlock in the test itself, not the CLI:

   The test starts a local `node:http` stub server (async) in the SAME
   process, then calls `spawnSync(...)` to launch the CLI as a child process
   and wait for it. `child_process.spawnSync` blocks the parent's Node.js
   event loop synchronously until the child exits — so the just-started
   http server can NEVER actually run its request handler while spawnSync is
   blocking. The child CLI's fetch() to the stub server hangs until its own
   15s fetchWithTimeout aborts it, producing "This operation was aborted" —
   exactly what all 3 failures show, after ~15s each.

   Verified with a minimal, unrelated repro (same architecture: http.createServer
   in-process + spawnSync child fetching it) — confirms the server's request
   handler never fires; the child is killed by the spawnSync timeout with no
   stdout/stderr at all. This is a structural bug: spawnSync can never work
   with an in-process async stub server no matter what the child does.

   Additionally, the stub server's fixture PAYMENT-REQUIRED header hardcodes
   `payTo: "0x0000000000000000000000000000000000dEaD"`, which is only 38 hex
   chars (one "0" short of a valid 20-byte / 40-hex-char address — the
   well-known "dead address" is `0x000000000000000000000000000000000000dEaD`,
   40 hex chars). viem's own `getAddress()` rejects it outright:
     `Address "0x0000000000000000000000000000000000dEaD" is invalid.`
   This means even if the deadlock above were fixed, the "cheap" (quote <=
   cap, signs successfully) sub-test would still fail at the real signing
   step, since REQ-221/REQ-222 require calling the SDK's own
   createPaymentPayload() (which validates the recipient address) rather than
   hand-rolling a payment payload.

   MANUAL VERIFICATION (bypassing the deadlocked test harness, using async
   `spawn` + `await` instead of `spawnSync`, and the real fixture payTo fixed
   to the correct 40-char dead address) confirms the CLI's actual REQ-135a
   behavior is correct in both directions:
     - quote $0.05 <= --max-quote-usd $0.10 → signs, submits, completes,
       exit 0, `{"url":".../fake.mp4", ...}`.
     - quote $0.50 >  --max-quote-usd $0.10 → aborts BEFORE
       createPaymentPayload is ever called (stub's `signedSubmit` stays
       false), exit 1, both the --json message and the non-json stderr text
       contain "Error: Quote $0.5000 exceeds --max-quote-usd $0.10 —
       aborting before signing." — matching /0\.5/ exactly as the test
       asserts.

2) test/integration/video.test.ts — "REQ-133" sub-test:
   `(chainModule as any).getChain = () => "solana";` attempts to reassign a
   property on an ES module namespace object obtained via `await import(...)`.
   ES module namespace objects are non-configurable/non-writable by the
   language specification (this holds for node:test's module-mock objects
   too, confirmed empirically: `TypeError: Cannot assign to read only
   property 'getChain'`). No source-side change can make an ESM namespace
   object mutable in strict mode; this is a test-authoring bug (the earlier
   `mock.module(...)` call at the top of the file is the correct way to stub
   getChain, and does work correctly for the file's OTHER video/wallet
   integration tests — this one sub-test's ad-hoc re-mutation attempt is the
   defect).

Per the project's rule ("NEVER weaken, skip, or delete a test to make it
pass. If a test contradicts the spec, STOP and report to main"), these 4
tests were left unmodified and are reported here for a human/architectural
decision, rather than silently worked around.
